\title{Dynamic Feedback in Ferromagnet/Spin-Hall Heterostructures}

\author{Ran Cheng}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Carnegie Mellon University, 5000 Forbes Avenue, Pittsburgh, PA 15213}

\author{Jian-Gang Zhu}
\affiliation{Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University, 5000 Forbes Avenue, Pittsburgh, PA 15213}

\author{Di Xiao}
\affiliation{Department of Physics, Carnegie Mellon University, 5000 Forbes Avenue, Pittsburgh, PA 15213}

\pacs{75.78.-n, 75.76.+j, 75.47.-m, 85.75.-d} 

\begin{abstract}

In ferromagnet/normal metal heterostructures, spin pumping and spin-transfer torques are two reciprocal processes that occur concomitantly. Their interplay introduces a dynamic feedback effect interconnecting energy dissipation channels of both magnetization and current. By solving the spin diffusion process in the presence of the spin Hall effect in the normal metal, we show that the dynamic feedback gives rise to: (i) a nonlinear magnetic damping that is crucial to sustain uniform steady-state oscillations of a spin Hall oscillator at large angles. (ii) a frequency dependent spin Hall magnetoimpedance that reduces to the spin Hall magnetoresistance in the dc limit.

\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\textit{Introduction.}---According to Lenz's law, electromotive force (emf) generated by Faraday's effect opposes the change of magnetic flux that causes the emf, which is a direct consequence of energy conservation~\cite{ref:Lenz}. In generic settings, Lenz's law dictates a universal principle on how a process is affected by its converse: feedback is always negative. For example, an electric motor also works as a dynamotor so that the induced emf counteracts the applied emf, and the total electric current flowing through its coil is attenuated. As a result, the effective resistance from the \textit{I--V} measurement is appreciably larger than the internal resistance of the coil.

Faraday's effect and Lenz's law have important manifestations even in artificial electromagnetics emerging from spintronics. When the profile of a background magnetization varies slowly over space and time, conduction electron spins will follow the magnetization orientation. By doing so, the electron wave function acquires a geometric phase changing with time. This phase is analogous to a time-varying magnetic flux and produces a spin emf (SMF)~\cite{ref:SMF,ref:Shengyuan}. As a feedback, electrons driven by the SMF react on the magnetization via the spin-transfer torque (STT)~\cite{ref:Bazaliy,ref:STT}. This STT results in a modified magnetic damping~\cite{ref:Zhang} that hinders the magnetization dynamics generating the SMF. In a parallel sense, if a magnetic texture is driven into spontaneous motion via STTs by an applied current, it in turn exerts SMFs on the electrons, leading to a modified electrical resistivity~\cite{ref:JDZang,ref:Schulz}. The feedback mechanism persists even when thermal and mechanical forces are taken into account~\cite{ref:heatpump}, or when strong spin-orbit coupling exists~\cite{ref:SOMF}. In all these cases, conduction electron spins couple to the magnetization at arbitrary space-time points in the bulk~\cite{ref:Hydro}. Therefore, one can \textit{locally} eliminate either the electron motion or the magnetization dynamics to obtain the feedback-induced renormalization of various response coefficients.

In ferromagnet (FM)/normal metal (NM) heterostructures, \textit{nonlocal} effects arise because conduction electrons and magnetization reside in different materials and couple only at the interface. In this regime, spin pumping plays the role of SMF, which refers to the generation of spin current from a precessing FM into the NM~\cite{ref:spinpumping,ref:Kajiwara}. The pumped spin current is accompanied by a backflow of spin current~\cite{ref:spinbattery}, which reacts on the FM through the STT~\cite{ref:Beger,ref:Slonczewski}. The combined effect of spin pumping and backflow-induced STT renormalizes the spin-mixing conductance at the interface~\cite{ref:backflow1}. However, in the presence of the spin Hall effect (SHE)~\cite{ref:SHE}, spin pumping and spin backflow are also connected by the combined effect of the SHE and its inverse process, which forms a feedback loop as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:loop}(a). This additional feedback mechanism, proportional to $\theta_s^2$ ($\theta_s$ is the spin Hall angle), was completely ignored in previous studies~\cite{ref:backflow3,ref:JX}. Nevertheless, the recently discovered spin Hall magnetoresistance (SMR)~\cite{ref:SMRexp1,ref:SMRexp2,ref:SMRtheory} reveals that physics at $\theta_s^2$ level is essential to the electron transport in FM/NM heterostructures. Therefore, it is tempting to ask whether the feedback effect at the $\theta_s^2$ order is important to the magnetization dynamics. In a reciprocal sense, if we apply an ac current density to the NM, the SHE will drive the magnetization precession via the STT, which in turn can pump spin current back into the NM and renormalize the resistivity by means of the inverse SHE. This is analogous to an ac electric motor accommodating the back emf of the dynamotor effect.

In this Letter, we show that the feedback effect qualitatively modifies the dynamical behavior of an FM/NM heterostructure. First, the feedback manifests as a novel nonlinear damping effect in the magnetization dynamics. It enables \textit{uniform} auto-oscillations of a spin Hall oscillator and prevents magnetic switching. If our proposed feedback mechanism is ignored, however, such stabilized auto-oscillations are possible only for localized soliton excitations~\cite{ref:Bullet,ref:Urazhdin} or for nanopillars with strong dipolar interaction~\cite{ref:Rezende}. Second, the feedback effect gives rise to a spin Hall magnetoimpedance in the electron transport which reduces to the observed SMR in the dc limit.

