For typical FMs, the magnetization dynamics is much slower than the spin relaxation rate in the NM so that $\omega\tau_{\mathrm{sf}}\ll1$. In this limit, the spin accumulation $\bm{\mu}(z,t)$ adapts to the instantaneous magnetization orientation and is kept quasi-equilibrium~\cite{ref:backflow3}. As a result, the spin dynamics described by Eq.~\eqref{eq:spindiff} reduces to a stationary spin diffusion process at any specified time. Retaining to second order in $\theta_s^2$, Eq.~\eqref{eq:spindiff} is solved as

